{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"21ec082b-98db-4cd8-8369-322fa871b5e6","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions). They contain the stack trace, exception type, and thread info.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (Mach-O), run your app with:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n./YourApp\n```\nCore files land in `/cores/core.<pid>`, which you can load in **lldb**:\n```bash\nlldb ./YourApp -c /cores/core.12345\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5d446690-0662-4d2e-bbb3-aef80adf82de","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":286},"id":"8c57e8ea-6652-41ff-abf3-10a0c75e6160","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:58:25.916Z","parentId":"8abd105f-4395-45c9-8f35-c596b119ff17"}
